Mafdet's co-signature on the Iron Compact Appeal was partly motivated by the Ash Plea's failure: the absence of a co-signature had allowed Midgaard to treat the Ash Plea as a bilateral matter rather than a five-city concern.
The Ash Plea period established the mercy-freight maritime route as a practical alternative to overland supply — a route Mafdet continued to develop through the recovery era.
Mafdet's Swift Court created the "disaster petition cargo" classification during the Ash Plea years, allowing Rakuen-bound freight to move under reduced tariff during declared shortage periods.
The classification required a Rakuen Bloom Council attestation of shortage conditions — the first formal document-exchange protocol between Mafdet and Rakuen, predating the later co-signature arrangement.
